{"id":"2208.02116","submitter":"Luuk Blaauw","authors":"Luuk J. Blaauw, Detlef Lohse, Sander G. Huisman","title":"Sodium chloride inhibits effective bubbly drag reduction in turbulent\n  bubbly Taylor-Couette flows","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1098/rsta.2022.0127","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Using the Taylor--Couette geometry we experimentally investigate the effect\nof salt on drag reduction caused by bubbles present in the flow. We combine\ntorque measurements with optical high-speed imaging to relate the bubble size\nto the drag experienced by the flow. Previous findings have shown that a small\npercentage of air (4%) can lead to dramatic drag reduction (40%). In contrast\nto previous laboratory experiments, which mainly used fresh water, we will vary\nthe salinity from fresh water to the average salinity of ocean water. We find\nthat the drag reduction is increasingly more inhibited for increasing salt\nconcentration; going from 40% for fresh water to just 15% for sea water. Salts\npresent in the working fluid inhibit coalescence events, resulting in smaller\nbubbles in the flow and with that, decreasing the drag reduction. Above a\ncritical salinity, increasing the salinity has no further effect on the bubble\nsizes in the flow and thus the drag experienced by the flow. Our new findings\ndemonstrate the importance of NaCl on the bubbly drag reduction mechanism, and\nwill further challenge the naval architects to implement promising air\nlubrication systems on marine vessels.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2022 14:49:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 28 Oct 2022 21:28:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-15"}
